What are mobile devices?

3
00:00:17,800 --> 00:00:33,800
Well, it's all of our devices.

4
00:00:33,800 --> 00:00:36,800
Mobile systems are mobile devices.

5
00:00:36,800 --> 00:00:37,800
What are mobile devices?

6
00:00:37,800 --> 00:00:40,800
Well, it's all of our devices that are mobile.

7
00:00:40,800 --> 00:00:45,800
Things like our iPhones, our iPads, our little mini-super computers

8
00:00:45,800 --> 00:00:50,800
that we keep in our pockets that store gigabytes, maybe even terabytes of data

9
00:00:50,800 --> 00:00:54,800
and are unbelievably powerful little computers.

10
00:00:54,800 --> 00:00:56,800
So what's the risk with these mobile devices?

11
00:00:56,800 --> 00:01:00,800
Well, it's the fact that they can store so much data nowadays

12
00:01:00,800 --> 00:01:02,800
and the fact that they're mobile.

13
00:01:02,800 --> 00:01:05,800
Because what inevitably happens is someone puts a bunch of data on this device

14
00:01:05,800 --> 00:01:07,800
that probably shouldn't be on there.

15
00:01:07,800 --> 00:01:11,800
And then they forget their device somewhere inevitably in the cab,

16
00:01:11,800 --> 00:01:13,800
in the airport, on the train.

17
00:01:13,800 --> 00:01:16,800
Let's talk about an example of this actually occurring.

18
00:01:16,800 --> 00:01:20,800
And it highlights just what the risks are with mobile devices.

19
00:01:20,800 --> 00:01:26,800
So there was a healthcare provider in the US, I think it was in Minnesota, in 2011.

20
00:01:26,800 --> 00:01:31,800
A employee of that company left their laptop in their car.

21
00:01:31,800 --> 00:01:36,800
The laptop had about 20 million records on it, on about 23,000 patients.

22
00:01:36,800 --> 00:01:41,800
And they left this laptop in their car when they wanted to do a Starbucks or something like that.

23
00:01:41,800 --> 00:01:45,800
And what inevitably happens, the laptop was stolen.

24
00:01:45,800 --> 00:01:50,800
There was a whole series of extremely unfortunate events that all occurred

25
00:01:50,800 --> 00:01:53,800
because of that lost one lost laptop.

26
00:01:53,800 --> 00:01:55,800
So what happened?

27
00:01:55,800 --> 00:01:57,800
Well, there was a lawsuit by the Auditor General.

28
00:01:57,800 --> 00:02:01,800
There was a giant settlement, millions of dollars with the Auditor General.

29
00:02:01,800 --> 00:02:05,800
Their CEO, COO, CFO were all fired and replaced.

30
00:02:05,800 --> 00:02:10,800
There was two class action lawsuits from patients whose data was potentially exposed.

31
00:02:10,800 --> 00:02:14,800
There was a settlement with the FTC.

32
00:02:14,800 --> 00:02:16,800
Over 170 jobs were cut.

33
00:02:16,800 --> 00:02:20,800
And as a final kick in the pants, they were delisted from the New York Stock Exchange.

34
00:02:20,800 --> 00:02:22,800
They were publicly traded company.

35
00:02:22,800 --> 00:02:28,800
All of this, all of these tragic events occurred because of one lost laptop.

36
00:02:28,800 --> 00:02:30,800
And then companies never recovered.

37
00:02:30,800 --> 00:02:32,800
I've checked on their stock price a couple times since then.

38
00:02:32,800 --> 00:02:33,800
And they've never recovered.

39
00:02:33,800 --> 00:02:35,800
They've never gotten back to the highs they were once at.

40
00:02:35,800 --> 00:02:37,800
And they don't actually exist anymore.

41
00:02:37,800 --> 00:02:38,800
They were bought out.

42
00:02:38,800 --> 00:02:44,800
So this whole tale of woe was because of one lost or stolen laptop.

43
00:02:44,800 --> 00:02:46,800
So let's spend a minute thinking about this.

44
00:02:46,800 --> 00:02:50,800
What would be the best way to have prevented this event from occurring?

45
00:02:50,800 --> 00:02:52,800
This lost or stolen laptop?

46
00:02:52,800 --> 00:02:55,800
And all the horrible things that happened afterwards?

47
00:02:55,800 --> 00:02:57,800
About a lot of you were thinking, hold drive encryption.

48
00:02:57,800 --> 00:03:01,800
They should have encrypted the entire contents of the hard drive.

49
00:03:01,800 --> 00:03:06,800
Because the whole idea behind hold drive encryption is, even if someone steals your laptop,

50
00:03:06,800 --> 00:03:09,800
they'll find that all the data is being encrypted.

51
00:03:09,800 --> 00:03:13,800
And don't get me wrong, hold drive encryption, excellent idea, defense and depth,

52
00:03:13,800 --> 00:03:16,800
have multiple layers of controls, all good.

53
00:03:16,800 --> 00:03:20,800
But there's actually more of a flaw in hold drive encryption than most people realize.

54
00:03:20,800 --> 00:03:25,800
And that is, while the hold drive encryption is amazing, it'll use, you know, like AES,

55
00:03:25,800 --> 00:03:30,800
256-based encryption, it's unbelievably difficult to break the encryption.

56
00:03:30,800 --> 00:03:34,800
But the problem is, if someone has stolen your laptop,

57
00:03:34,800 --> 00:03:38,800
how long do they have to figure out how to break that encryption?

58
00:03:38,800 --> 00:03:43,800
And do they, in fact, need that extremely difficult to find 256-bit key?

59
00:03:43,800 --> 00:03:44,800
No.

60
00:03:44,800 --> 00:03:50,800
What they, in fact, need to unlock that excellent encryption is the user's password.

61
00:03:50,800 --> 00:03:53,800
And how good are our user's passwords?

62
00:03:53,800 --> 00:03:54,800
Horrible.

63
00:03:54,800 --> 00:03:57,800
The most common password in the world is password.

64
00:03:57,800 --> 00:04:01,800
So an attacker that steals a laptop that has hold drive encryption

65
00:04:01,800 --> 00:04:06,800
has an unlimited amount of time to try and discover probably a very bad password.

66
00:04:06,800 --> 00:04:10,800
And you might be saying, oh, but lots of laptops have protection mechanisms that only allow you

67
00:04:10,800 --> 00:04:12,800
to try a password so many times.

68
00:04:12,800 --> 00:04:17,800
Well, those mechanisms are pretty easy to defeat if you have physical control of a laptop

69
00:04:17,800 --> 00:04:18,800
of its in your possession.

70
00:04:18,800 --> 00:04:23,800
So hold drive encryption, not a bad control, but not the best way for preventing this.

71
00:04:23,800 --> 00:04:24,800
Okay.

72
00:04:24,800 --> 00:04:28,800
What about remote white capabilities?

73
00:04:28,800 --> 00:04:33,800
Lots of cell phones and even some laptops have the ability to remotely wipe the device.

74
00:04:33,800 --> 00:04:38,800
Again, not a bad control, but not as good as most people think.

75
00:04:38,800 --> 00:04:43,800
Because what's required for that remote white capability to be activated?

76
00:04:43,800 --> 00:04:48,800
The device has to be sent a signal and the device has to receive that signal.

77
00:04:48,800 --> 00:04:49,800
And he's skilled attacker.

78
00:04:49,800 --> 00:04:52,800
Soon as they steal a laptop, what are they going to do?

79
00:04:52,800 --> 00:04:55,800
Well, they're going to put that laptop in a fair day cage,

80
00:04:55,800 --> 00:04:59,800
in an envelope in something that's going to block that signal from being received.

81
00:04:59,800 --> 00:05:02,800
And then when they get it back to their criminal layer and their parents' basement,

82
00:05:02,800 --> 00:05:05,800
they're going to put themselves in this fair day cage.

83
00:05:05,800 --> 00:05:12,800
And so that laptop, is it ever going to receive that kill switch that signal to wipe the drive?

84
00:05:12,800 --> 00:05:13,800
Of course not.

85
00:05:13,800 --> 00:05:17,800
Now, for reasons, I decided to look into this a little bit.

86
00:05:17,800 --> 00:05:20,800
I thought, you know, let's find out how expensive it is to get one of these sleeves

87
00:05:20,800 --> 00:05:23,800
that you can put a laptop in a fair day cage, essentially.

88
00:05:23,800 --> 00:05:28,800
So I went on Amazon and on Amazon.com, like 2030 bucks, you can get a nice haul quality one.

89
00:05:28,800 --> 00:05:30,800
I was like, that's pretty good, not too bad.

90
00:05:30,800 --> 00:05:32,800
Then I was like, I bet you can do better.

91
00:05:32,800 --> 00:05:35,800
So I went to Alibaba, straight from China, right?

92
00:05:35,800 --> 00:05:38,800
On Alibaba, as long as you're willing to buy like 500 of them,

93
00:05:38,800 --> 00:05:40,800
you get them for like three bucks a piece.

94
00:05:40,800 --> 00:05:41,800
Pretty darn good.

95
00:05:41,800 --> 00:05:44,800
But then I thought, you know what? I can do even better.

96
00:05:44,800 --> 00:05:46,800
So it turns out, bag of chips.

97
00:05:46,800 --> 00:05:50,800
If you open up a bag of chips, you see that silver lining inside, it's mylar.

98
00:05:50,800 --> 00:05:52,800
It's a pretty good blocker of radio waves.

99
00:05:53,800 --> 00:05:57,800
So you go to Costco, buy yourselves a jumbo bag of chips, you got snacks,

100
00:05:57,800 --> 00:06:00,800
you got the fair day cage you need, there you go.

101
00:06:00,800 --> 00:06:03,800
You can defeat the remote wipe capability.

102
00:06:03,800 --> 00:06:08,800
So what's the best answer for how we prevent this type of mobile data breach?

103
00:06:08,800 --> 00:06:13,800
The best answer in fact is to not have the data on the laptop.

104
00:06:13,800 --> 00:06:18,800
If there isn't sensitive data on the laptop, then there's no worries about that laptop being lost or stolen,

105
00:06:18,800 --> 00:06:21,800
which is inevitably going to happen.

106
00:06:21,800 --> 00:06:26,800
So it turns out, one of the best ways of preventing these types of breaches is policies,

107
00:06:26,800 --> 00:06:29,800
procedures, user awareness training, and education,

108
00:06:29,800 --> 00:06:34,800
so that users know not to store highly sensitive data on their mobile devices.

109
00:06:34,800 --> 00:06:39,800
So when we think about how do we reduce the risk of mobile devices,

110
00:06:39,800 --> 00:06:42,800
one of the best ways is through policy, education, awareness.

111
00:06:42,800 --> 00:06:46,800
And then of course, do have the other physically and the other controls in place,

112
00:06:46,800 --> 00:06:49,800
still a very good idea, defense and depth to have things like whole drive encryption,

113
00:06:49,800 --> 00:06:54,800
to have remote wipe capabilities, to have good anti-malware capabilities, whatever.

114
00:06:54,800 --> 00:06:58,800
You know, still use all those controls, but the best one, training and awareness.

115
00:06:58,800 --> 00:07:03,800
Now let's talk about a couple of other controls that are really important to have with mobile devices.

